.LI "\ \ "
If the process type is \*LDir-User\*O, the
IPC server ID displayed refers to the GDS (IPC) server
(for example, \*LDUA-cache\*O, \*LC-stub\*O, \*LDSA\*O) with which this
GDS client is associated.  The relationship between IPCID and DIRID is 
important, because it is easy to find the correct 
DSA or S-Stub if the directory ID is known. 
(The relationship for \*LS-Stub\*O processes is \*LDir ID = IPCID - 10\*O; 
the relationship for DSA processes is \*LDir ID = IPCID - 30\*O).
.LI "\*LSTATE\*O"
Describes the state of
a GDS process during the startup phase or of a GDS client. 
...\" Table 16-5 
Table 5-3 shows the valid states and their meanings.
.P
If none of the specific states shown in 
...\" Table 16-4 
Table 5-3 is associated with the process, a dash is printed.  
.LE
.P
Table 5-3 shows how a GDS process during the startup phase is designated by
a state value of W\*En\*O.  GDS clients refer to any application.
They are represented by \*LDir-User\*O in \*Lgdsdirinfo\*O output.
.P
